---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const ACTION_NETWORK_URL = "https://actionnetwork.org/petitions/audit-and-account-for-flock-surveillance-in-graham-county";

const requestText = `To the Records Custodian:

Under the Arizona Public Records Law (A.R.S. Section 39-121 et seq.),
I request to inspect and obtain copies of the following records
regarding your agency's use of Flock Safety automated license plate
reader (ALPR) cameras, for the period of the last 12 months:

1. The Flock "Network Audit" report(s) showing all searches of your
   agency's camera data conducted by external or outside agencies,
   including the searching agency, date, and the stated reason or
   case number for each search.

2. The Flock "Organization Audit" report(s) showing all searches
   conducted by your own personnel, including user, date, and the
   stated reason or case number for each search.

3. Your agency's current Flock data-sharing configuration, including
   which agencies, states, or networks your data is shared with, and
   whether federal sharing is enabled or disabled.

4. Any policy, procedure, or memorandum of understanding governing
   your agency's use of Flock or ALPR data.

5. The total number of cameras operated, and the data retention
   period currently configured.

If any portion of these records is withheld, please cite the specific
statutory basis for withholding and provide all reasonably segregable
non-exempt portions.

Please advise of any fees before fulfilling this request. I am willing
to inspect records in person to minimize costs.

Thank you.

[Your name]
[Your contact information]
[Date]`;
---

<Layout title="Take Action">
  <div class="content">
    <span class="card-tag tag-act">Act</span>
    <h1>Three Things You Can Do</h1>
    <p class="subtitle" style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: 1.15rem;">
      Sign the petition. File the records request. Show up at the meeting. That's the exact path five Arizona towns walked to get Flock out. Do all three.
    </p>

    <h2 id="petition">1. Sign the Petition</h2>
    <p>
      We, the undersigned residents and neighbors of Graham County, are concerned about the Flock Safety surveillance cameras operating on our roads. These cameras log every vehicle that passes and feed a national network that thousands of outside agencies can search. Across Arizona, that same network has been misused: one Phoenix-area department ran over 12,000 searches, an officer logged an ethnic slur as a search reason, and agencies used it to track people at protests.
    </p>
    <p>
      We are not asking our police to stop solving crimes. We are asking our local government to be transparent about a powerful tool bought in our name. <strong>Our goal is to get these cameras removed, as Sedona, Flagstaff, South Tucson, Cochise County, and Sierra Vista already have.</strong> At minimum, if they stay, we call on the City of Safford and the Graham County Board of Supervisors to:
    </p>
    <div class="card">
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>Release the Flock network audit</strong>, the full log of every outside agency that has searched our cameras' data, and the stated reason for each search.</li>
        <li><strong>Disable federal and out-of-state data sharing</strong> by default, so our local data is not silently fed into ICE or other federal systems.</li>
        <li><strong>Hold a public hearing</strong> before any Flock contract is renewed, with the audit results presented to residents first.</li>
        <li><strong>Adopt a written ALPR use policy</strong> with real penalties for misuse.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <p>Show us who is watching. That is not too much to ask in a free country.</p>
    <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: 0.95rem;">
      We host this on <strong>Action Network</strong>, the platform built for grassroots organizing. No ad-tracking on signers. Your signature is between you, us, and the officials we deliver it to.
    </p>
    <!-- Action Network embedded petition form -->
    <!-- is:inline is REQUIRED: the AN bootstrap relies on document.currentScript,
         which Astro's default script bundling would break. Do not remove. -->
    <link href="https://actionnetwork.org/css/style-embed-v3.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" />
    <script is:inline src="https://actionnetwork.org/widgets/v6/petition/audit-and-account-for-flock-surveillance-in-graham-county?format=js&source=widget"></script>
    <div id="can-petition-area-audit-and-account-for-flock-surveillance-in-graham-county" style="width: 100%"></div>
    <p style="margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-muted);">
      Form not loading? You can also <a href={ACTION_NETWORK_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">sign directly on Action Network &rarr;</a>
    </p>

    <h2 id="records">2. File a Records Request</h2>
    <p>
      Arizona's public records law (A.R.S. &sect; 39-121) gives any person the right to inspect public records. Flock search logs are public records. No lawyer, no reason needed. The most useful document is the <strong>Network Audit</strong>, the log of every outside agency that searched our cameras' data, the same report that exposed abuse in Dayton, Bend, and San Francisco. File it with both custodians:
    </p>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>City of Safford &mdash; for Safford PD cameras</h3>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>City Clerk's Office</strong> (records custodian), 717 W. Main St., Safford AZ 85546 &middot; Mailing: P.O. Box 272, Safford AZ 85548</li>
        <li><strong>Clerk phone:</strong> 928-432-4000 &middot; Safford PD records: 928-432-4100</li>
        <li>Records info: <strong>cityofsafford.us</strong> (Records section)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Graham County &mdash; for Sheriff's Office cameras</h3>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>Graham County Sheriff's Office</strong>, 921 W. Thatcher Blvd., Safford AZ 85546</li>
        <li><strong>Phone:</strong> 928-428-3141 &middot; Sheriff P.J. Allred</li>
        <li>Records Division: <strong>graham.az.gov/247/Records</strong></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-muted);">
      Neither office publishes a records-request email, so file by mail or in person, or call the clerk's line to ask where to send it. We don't list an email we can't confirm.
    </p>
    <p>Copy this, fill in the three bracketed lines, and send it:</p>
    <div class="codeblock" id="request">{requestText}</div>
    <button class="btn" id="copy-btn" type="button">Copy the Request</button>

    <h2 id="meetings">3. Show Up at the Meeting</h2>
    <p>
      A signature is a number. A neighbor at the podium is a problem the council has to answer. These two bodies hold the Flock contracts, their meetings are public, and you have the right to speak.
    </p>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Safford City Council</h3>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>When:</strong> usually 2nd &amp; 4th Monday, 6:00 PM (holiday bumps to Tuesday; some months vary, check the agenda)</li>
        <li><strong>Where:</strong> Safford Library Program Room, 808 S. 7th Ave.</li>
        <li>Agendas: cityofsafford.us &rarr; Agenda Center &middot; "Citizen Comments on Non-Agenda Items" is your slot</li>
      </ul>
      <a href={`${base}safford-city-council.ics`} class="btn" style="margin-top: 0.5rem;" download>Add to Calendar</a>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Graham County Board of Supervisors</h3>
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>When:</strong> 1st &amp; 3rd Monday (holiday bumps to Tuesday)</li>
        <li><strong>Where:</strong> Graham County General Services Building, Assembly Room, 921 W. Thatcher Blvd.</li>
        <li>Agendas: graham.az.gov &rarr; Meetings and Agendas &middot; Questions: 928-428-3250</li>
      </ul>
      <a href={`${base}graham-county-supervisors.ics`} class="btn" style="margin-top: 0.5rem;" download>Add to Calendar</a>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-muted);">
      Always confirm the date on the official agenda before you go, schedules shift around holidays and budget season.
    </p>

    <h3>A Two-Minute Script You Can Read</h3>
    <blockquote>
      My name is ___ and I live in ___. The Flock cameras on our roads feed a national network thousands of outside agencies can search. On that same network, one Phoenix-area department ran over twelve thousand searches, an officer logged an ethnic slur as a reason, and Arizona agencies used it to track people at protests. I'm not asking our police to stop solving crimes. I'm asking this body to request our network audit and hold a public hearing before the Flock contract is renewed. Show us who is watching. Thank you.
    </blockquote>

    <h2>How to Make It Land</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>Bring receipts, not vibes.</strong> Name the Scottsdale searches, the Glendale slur, the Tempe protest searches. Real Arizona facts beat "I heard."</li>
        <li><strong>Keep it to one ask.</strong> Request the audit and a hearing before renewal. One clear request lands harder than five.</li>
        <li><strong>Don't go alone.</strong> Three neighbors at the same meeting is a pattern the council notices. One is an anecdote.</li>
        <li><strong>Back the police and still say no.</strong> Flagstaff did exactly that. "No reflection on the department" disarms the room.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>More Tools</h2>
    <p>
      You're not alone in this. The national movement has maps, model bills, and organizers:
      <a href="https://deflock.me" target="_blank" rel="noopener">deflock.me</a> (camera map),
      the <a href="https://www.aclu.org/get-the-flock-out-toolkit" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ACLU "Get the Flock Out" toolkit</a> (model bills, organizer directory), and
      <a href="https://deflocktucson.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DeFlock Tucson</a>, the Arizona chapter that helped push South Tucson to cancel.
    </p>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.getElementById('copy-btn')?.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const text = document.getElementById('request')?.innerText || '';
      navigator.clipboard.writeText(text).then(() => {
        const btn = document.getElementById('copy-btn');
        if (btn) { btn.textContent = 'Copied'; setTimeout(() => { btn.textContent = 'Copy the Request'; }, 2000); }
      });
    });
  </script>
</Layout>
